default19. 
defaultThere are several reasons why it is important to reflect on the high presence of climate sceptic voices in the UK print media, and particularly the opinion pages.  The first is that much of the uncontested scept
defaultic opinion is written by in-house columnists and not climate scientists.  Th
defaultis could give the impression to a general audience that climate science is 
defaulta matter of opinion or merely
default ‘a point of view’, in the same way as many political issues are, without gi
defaultving the readers a sense of what most climate scientists 
defaultsay is the case about rising temperatures and the 
defaultcauses of 
defaultthem
default.
default20. 
defaultA second important aspect to consider is the effect on readers of the promulgation of uncertainty, and in particular the view oft
defaulten put forward by sceptics that there is significant disagreement amongst scientists.  There is evidence from a recent study carried out with focus groups in the UK that many people believe that there is a lack of consensus in scientific opinion, partly be
defaultcause this is frequently 
defaultthe way climate science is presented in the media.  The participants thought that scientists are often in disagreement with each other or change their mind over time
default (
defaultShuckburgh
default et al, 2012)
default.  
