default23. Part of the 
defaultchallenge
default is that scientific uncertainty is ofte
defaultn misunderstood, particularly by the general public, and misinterpreted as ignorance.  For example, many people fail to recognise the distinction between ‘school science’, which 
defaultis 
defaulta
default source of solid facts and reliable understanding
default, and ‘research science’ 
defaultwhere uncertainty is engrained and is often the impetus for further investigation. Risk on the other hand is an essential part of everyday experience, including the worlds of insurance, health and investment.   
default23.  
defaultThe RISJ
default 
default2013 
defaultstudy, which looked at mo
defaultre than 300 articles 
defaulton climate change 
defaultin the print media in six countries, found that the media on the whole overwhelmingly use a narrative of ‘disasters’ and ‘uncertainty’, when reporting climate change. 
defaultThe language of risk (and of opportunity) was much
default less prevalent.  
defaultStudies show that d
defaultisaster and uncertainty frames – at least in their more extreme forms - are not usually seen as enhancing public understanding, engagement or behaviour change
default (Moser and 
defaultDilling
default 2004, O’Neill and Nicholson-Cole, 2010)
