default24. 
defaultRecommendationsdefaultMore research 
defaultis needed 
defaultinto the effect of certain messages
default about climate change
default in the media and elsewhere on public understanding, e
defaultngagement and behaviour change. It is often wrongly assumed that simply giving the public more infor
defaultmation about climate science will promote ‘better’ engagement, when most communication theory suggests that most people filter information about climate science through their cultural values.  Dialogue and discussion are 
defaultoften 
defaultmore effective than top-down 
defaultinformation. 
defaultScientific uncertainty about climate change (for example, the timing, severity and location of 
defaultfuture 
defaultimpact
defaults
default) is particularly difficult to convey without confusing the public. More work need
defaults
default to be done on 
defaulttesting 
defaultwhat sort of messages 
defaultand l
defaultanguage 
defaultmight help
default with what sectors of society
default, and whether risk is a more productive language.
